column6: Hi! We will start soon.
Welcome! I'm Clem.

Tell the team your name and share something about yourself, such as a hobby you have or a game you like to play. Ask questions about what the others share. Take a couple of minutes to learn more about each other.
Hi I'm Amy
Hello, Amy.
Okay, we're starting.

In this activity, your team will examine evidence of climate change in the form of graphs and experimental data. You will be asked to identify what the evidence tells you and what questions you still have. Then, you will read a local mayor’s opinion on fossil fuels and develop an argument in response.
We will examine data about how temperature change, carbon dioxide, and fossil fuels may play a role in climate change.
Amy, you will lead a discussion about carbon dioxide and climate change.
If others join you later, they will lead discussions on the other roles.
First, click on the words "Temperature Change Data" at the upper left. Examine the graph and take about 5 minutes to discuss as a team.

If someone has not yet been assigned a role, ask them to lead this discussion by sharing their thoughts and asking the team about their ideas. What does the evidence tell you? Does it lead to further questions?
Type "ready" when you have finished discussing the temperature change data.
Okay, let's get ready to move on. Remember to type "ready" if you're done with this step.
Next, click on the words "Carbon Dioxide Data" at the upper left. Examine the tables and take about 5 minutes to discuss as a team.
Amy, you take the lead this time. Is the evidence convincing? Could there be other causes for the effects?
Type "ready" when you have finished discussing the carbon dioxide data.
Okay, let's get ready to move on. Remember to type "ready" if you're done with this step.
Now, click on the words "Fossil Fuels Data" at the upper left. Examine the graph and take about 5 minutes to discuss as a team.
If someone has not yet led a discussion, it's their turn to take the lead. How does this data relate to climate change?
Type "ready" when you have finished discussing the fossil fuels data.
We need to start wrapping up. Remember to type "ready" when you're ready to move on.

Okay, it's time to move on to the next part of the activity. First, spend a few minutes reading and thinking about the letter from the mayor that you'll find when you click on "Mayoral Letter" at the left.
Type "ready" when you have finished examining the mayor's letter.
We need to start wrapping up. Remember to type "ready" when you're ready to move on.

Before developing your response to Mayor Williams, summarize her perspective. What are the benefits of using fossil fuels? What evidence and reasoning does she use to support her decision? Discuss for a few minutes.
Type "ready" when you have finished summarizing and discussing the mayor's letter.
Okay, let's get ready to move on. Remember to type "ready" if you're done with this step.

Now, spend the rest of your time discussing and developing a response to the mayor. Click on "Joint Response" at the left for the form you will complete together. You can logout of the agent when you're done.
How would you respond to the mayor from the standpoint of the discussion you led on a climate change role? Make sure to support your ideas with evidence.
hhihi
i'm back
can we start again
It is time for us to wrap up now. It has been a pleasure working with you. The activity is now over.
Have a nice day!
